  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States and internationally:\n\n1. U.S. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate record-keeping for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Criminalize concealing the source of illegally obtained money\n- Impose penalties and fines for non-compliance\n\n3. International Frameworks:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- International monetary regulations\n\n4. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\n5. Penalties:\n- Significant monetary fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income and track potential financial crimes.",
